<subSubSection box="[199,1437,1734,1761]" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1482,2013]" box="[199,1437,1734,1761]" pageId="8" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1734,1760]" pageId="8" pageNumber="39">Distribution.</emphasis>
Lord Howe Rise in the SW Pacific, and the Ross Sea, Pacific Antarctic Ridge (
<figureCitation box="[1205,1268,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,2018,2042]" captionTargetBox="[182,1409,309,1989]" captionTargetId="figure-94@5.[178,1409,309,1995]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution of the three described species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6911233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6911233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="39">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); 
<quantity box="[1291,1432,1735,1761]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.057" metricValueMax="1.636" metricValueMin="0.4779999999999999" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="1057.0" valueMax="1636.0" valueMin="478.0">478–1636 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1482,2013]" pageId="8" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1770,1796]" pageId="8" pageNumber="39">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Corallum planar and densely branched to second and third order; pinnules bilateral and alternating, usually less than 
<quantity box="[342,397,1807,1833]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" unit="cm" value="1.0">1 cm</quantity>
long (maximum 
<quantity box="[589,649,1807,1833]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
); pinnular density 11–16 per 
<quantity box="[973,1028,1807,1833]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
(total for both rows); polypar spines up to 
<quantity box="[220,308,1843,1869]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.1 mm</quantity>
tall; abpolypar spines up to 
<quantity box="[640,742,1843,1869]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="0.09">0.09 mm</quantity>
tall; 4–5 spines per mm in each row; polyps up to 
<quantity box="[1338,1405,1843,1869]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
in transverse diameter; polyp density 2.5 per cm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1482,2013]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1437,151,1653]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="8" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1914,1940]" pageId="8" pageNumber="39">Description.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[401,499,1915,1941]" pageId="8" pageNumber="39">holotype</typeStatus>
(NIWA 88617) is a complete colony approximately 
<quantity box="[1081,1149,1915,1941]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" unit="cm" value="28.0">28 cm</quantity>
tall and 
<quantity box="[1244,1312,1915,1941]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" unit="cm" value="17.0">17 cm</quantity>
wide, with a basal stem diameter of about 
<quantity box="[494,558,1951,1977]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[572,662,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[169,1418,196,1921]" captionTargetId="figure-28@10.[169,1418,181,1921]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 4. Diplopathes gen. nov. multipinnata sp. nov., holotype, NIWA 88617: A. corallum; B. sections of pinnules showing spines (B from schizoholotype, USNM 1491425, SEM stub 457). The larger projections on the right side of the pinnules are the polypar spines." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6911245" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6911245/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="39">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). It is branched mostly to the second order. The stem and branches are pinnulate; the pinnules are placed in two lateral rows and also arranged in an alternating pattern; there are no signs of more than two rows of pinnules on any part of the corallum. The unpinnulated basal part of the stem is 
<quantity box="[1359,1436,151,177]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="2.4">2.4 cm</quantity>
long, and the stem extends to the top of the corallum. Most of the pinnules originating on the stem are developed into pinnulated branches which can be 
<quantity box="[540,610,223,249]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
or more in length. On the lower part of the stem the pinnules are 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="4.4" metricValueMin="3.6" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="4.4" valueMin="3.6">3.6–4.4 mm</quantity>
apart on each side of the axis, resulting in a total of 15–16 pinnules per 
<quantity box="[998,1057,259,285]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
. A similar pinnular density occurs on the upper part of the stem and on most of the branches; although in a few locations the pinnules are much further apart resulting in as few as 11 pinnules per 
<quantity box="[632,691,331,357]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
. The pinnules are mostly 
<quantity box="[975,1030,331,357]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="1.0">1 cm</quantity>
or less in length; however, some are up to 
<quantity box="[214,290,366,393]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="1.5">1.5 cm</quantity>
long. Fusions occur among the pinnules, especially on the outer parts of the corallum. The pinnules on the lower part of the stem do not become pinnulated for a distance of up to 
<quantity box="[1005,1081,402,429]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="2.5">2.5 cm</quantity>
from the stem, thus giving that part of the corallum a more open appearance along the stem. In most other places on stem and branches the distance to the first pinnules is 0.5 to 1.0 cm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">
The spines (
<figureCitation box="[340,429,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[169,1418,196,1921]" captionTargetId="figure-28@10.[169,1418,181,1921]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 4. Diplopathes gen. nov. multipinnata sp. nov., holotype, NIWA 88617: A. corallum; B. sections of pinnules showing spines (B from schizoholotype, USNM 1491425, SEM stub 457). The larger projections on the right side of the pinnules are the polypar spines." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6911245" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6911245/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
) on the pinnules are conical, smooth, with a rounded apex. The polypar and abpolypar spines are nearly equal in size. The spines are about as wide at the base (in an axial direction) as they are tall. On pinnules 
<quantity box="[253,416,582,609]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1999999999999993" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.31999999999999995" valueMax="0.35" valueMin="0.29">0.29–0.35 mm</quantity>
in diameter, the polypar spines are 
<quantity box="[812,975,583,609]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.899999999999999" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="7.8" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.089" valueMax="0.1" valueMin="0.078">0.078‒0.1 mm</quantity>
tall, the abpolypar spines 
<quantity box="[1267,1433,582,609]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.07" valueMax="0.09" valueMin="0.05">0.05‒0.09 mm</quantity>
. The spines are arranged in axial rows, with 3‒6 rows visible in lateral view. Within the rows, the spines are spaced 
<quantity box="[151,314,655,681]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.05" metricValueMax="3.7" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.305" valueMax="0.37" valueMin="0.24">0.24‒0.37 mm</quantity>
apart, resulting in 4–5 spines per mm. The size and density of the polyps could not be determined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">
<materialsCitation collectionCode="NIWA" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" specimenCode="NIWA 95270, NIWA 95271, NIWA 95273" specimenCount="2">
Three 
<typeStatus box="[271,506,691,717]" isOtherTypeStatus="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">additional specimens</typeStatus>
are assigned to this species. All are similar to the 
<typeStatus box="[1058,1156,691,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">holotype</typeStatus>
in having fusions among neighboring pinnules and in having relatively small spines that are equally wide as tall. In 
<specimenCode box="[1142,1292,726,753]" collectionCode="NIWA" country="New Zealand" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/nyq3-3g6s" name="National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" type="Other institutional type">NIWA 95270</specimenCode>
, the pinnules reach a maximum length of 
<quantity box="[467,547,762,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="2.5">2.5 cm</quantity>
; there are 14‒15 pinnules per 
<quantity box="[885,944,763,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
; and the polypar spines are 
<quantity box="[1256,1356,763,789]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.08">0.08 mm</quantity>
tall. In 
<specimenCode box="[151,302,798,825]" collectionCode="NIWA" country="New Zealand" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/nyq3-3g6s" name="National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" type="Other institutional type">NIWA 95271</specimenCode>
, the pinnules are up to 
<quantity box="[557,611,799,825]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
long; there are 16–17 pinnules per 
<quantity box="[1003,1061,799,825]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
, and the spines are up to 
<quantity box="[1337,1437,799,825]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.08">0.08 mm</quantity>
tall. In 
<specimenCode box="[233,386,834,861]" collectionCode="NIWA" country="New Zealand" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/nyq3-3g6s" name="National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" type="Other institutional type">NIWA 95273</specimenCode>
, the pinnules are up to 
<quantity box="[651,707,835,861]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
long; there are 14‒15 pinnules per 
<quantity box="[1112,1168,835,861]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
and the spines are 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.08">0.08 mm</quantity>
tall. In this last colony the polyps were found to be 
<quantity box="[772,886,870,897]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.75" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="3.75" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.5">3.5–4 mm</quantity>
in transverse diameter, with a density of ~2.5 per cm
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,365,942,968]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">Comparisons.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[374,664,943,969]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="multipinnata">
<emphasis box="[374,664,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">Diplopathes multipinnata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[878,1029,943,969]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis box="[878,898,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[915,1029,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[1088,1263,943,969]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tuatoruensis">
<emphasis box="[1088,1108,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1125,1263,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">tuatoruensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below) in having a much more densely branched corallum. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[742,921,979,1005]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="multipinnata">
<emphasis box="[742,762,979,1004]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[778,921,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">multipinnata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
almost every pinnule originating on the stem becomes pinnulated, whereas in the other two species only a few of the stem pinnules develop into branches. In addition, the length of the pinnules (
<quantity box="[569,703,1050,1077]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="2.25" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.5">1.5 to 3 cm</quantity>
) is less than that of the other two species (
<tableCitation box="[1196,1285,1051,1077]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,239,998,1024]" captionText="TABLE 3. Comparison of morphometric characters in the three species of Diplopathes gen. nov." pageId="9" pageNumber="40">Table 3</tableCitation>
). The size of the polypar spines (
<quantity box="[379,533,1087,1113]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.09" valueMax="0.1" valueMin="0.08">0.08–0.1 mm</quantity>
) is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[785,936,1087,1113]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis box="[785,805,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[822,936,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity box="[954,1112,1087,1113]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="9.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.095" valueMax="0.1" valueMin="0.09">0.09–0.1 mm</quantity>
), but greater than that in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tuatoruensis">
<emphasis box="[1409,1429,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,289,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">tuatoruensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity box="[305,503,1122,1149]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.05" metricValueMax="4.6" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.0405" valueMax="0.046" valueMin="0.035">
<geoCoordinate box="[305,368,1122,1149]" degrees="0.035" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" precision="55" value="0.035">0.035</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[368,447,1122,1149]" degrees="0.046" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" precision="55" value="-0.046">–0.046</geoCoordinate>
mm
</quantity>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[523,811,1123,1149]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="multipinnata">
<emphasis box="[523,811,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">Diplopathes multipinnata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also more similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[1081,1230,1123,1148]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis box="[1081,1230,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D. antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having slightly larger polyps than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[360,532,1159,1185]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tuatoruensis">
<emphasis box="[360,380,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[394,532,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">tuatoruensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">
In general appearance 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[454,742,1195,1221]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="multipinnata">
<emphasis box="[454,742,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">Diplopathes multipinnata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Opresko &amp; Breedy, 2010" authorityName="Opresko &amp; Breedy" authorityYear="2010" box="[892,1433,1195,1221]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Lillipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="ritamariae">
<emphasis box="[892,1139,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">Lillipathes ritamariae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko, D. M. &amp; Breedy, O." box="[1147,1433,1195,1221]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" pagination="234 - 241" refId="ref11385" refString="Opresko, D. M. &amp; Breedy, O. (2010) A new species of antipatharian coral (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Antipatharia: Schizopathidae) from the Pacific coast of Costa Rica. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 123 (3), 234 - 241. https: // doi. org / 10.2988 / 10 - 06.1" type="journal article" year="2010">Opresko &amp; Breedy, 2010</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter species forms large densely branched flabellate colonies with pinnules that are alternately arranged in two lateral rows over much of the corallum, but in four rows on some branches, especially near the distal ends of the branches. In both species many branches and pinnules become fused together. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Breedy" authorityYear="2010" box="[1102,1252,1303,1329]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Lillipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="ritamariae">
<emphasis box="[1102,1118,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1132,1252,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">ritamariae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the pinnules are up to 
<quantity box="[219,297,1338,1365]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="1.5">1.5 cm</quantity>
long, the density of the pinnules is 10–14 per cm when four rows are present, and 14–16 per 
<quantity box="[1379,1436,1339,1365]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
when only two rows are present; the polypar spines are up to 
<quantity box="[845,946,1375,1401]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="0.12">0.12 mm</quantity>
tall, and the polyps are mostly 
<quantity box="[1301,1437,1375,1401]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="2.4">2.4–2.6 mm</quantity>
in transverse diameter (3–3.5 per cm). The major differences between the two species are in the size of the polyps and in the presence of four rows of pinnules in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Breedy" authorityYear="2010" box="[680,829,1447,1473]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Lillipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="ritamariae">
<emphasis box="[680,696,1447,1472]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[709,829,1447,1472]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">ritamariae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,420,1482,1508]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">Genetic Distances.</emphasis>
A K2P-based genetic distance analysis based on 
<emphasis box="[984,1099,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">cox3-cox1</emphasis>
indicated a 0.61% separation between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[255,435,1519,1545]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="multipinnata">
<emphasis box="[255,275,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[292,435,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">multipinnata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(NIWA 88617) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[676,827,1519,1545]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis box="[676,696,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[713,827,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(NIWA 38070), and a 1.29% separation between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="multipinnata">
<emphasis box="[1409,1429,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,294,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">multipinnata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(NIWA 88617) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opresko &amp; Stewart &amp; Voza &amp; Tracey &amp; Brugler" authorityYear="2022" box="[523,695,1555,1581]" class="Anthozoa" family="Schizopathidae" genus="Diplopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tuatoruensis">
<emphasis box="[523,543,1555,1580]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[557,695,1555,1580]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">tuatoruensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(NIWA 16055).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="40" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1591,1617]" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[825,900,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">multus</emphasis>
, much, and 
<emphasis box="[1036,1104,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="40">penna</emphasis>
, feather, in reference to many pinnulated branches on the colony.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
